Title: The Tell-Tale Heart
Credit: Written by
Author: Edgar Allan Poe
Source: Adapted from book
Draft date: 3/25/2025
Notes: Gothic period live-action; candlelit interiors; closed cast; confessional tone

FADE IN:

INT. DARK CHAMBER - NIGHT

A single candle. Close on THE NARRATOR: a lean man in his thirties, pale, dark hollowed eyes, neat dark coat and waistcoat of the 1840s, hair smoothed back, hands too still. He faces us—calm, precise, almost smiling.

NARRATOR
True!—nervous—very, very dreadfully nervous I had been and am; but why will you say that I am mad? The disease had sharpened my senses—not destroyed—not dulled them. Above all was the sense of hearing acute. I heard all things in the heaven and in the earth. I heard many things in hell. How, then, am I mad? Hearken! and observe how healthily—how calmly I can tell you the whole story.

He leans a fraction closer. Behind him, shadows of an old house.

NARRATOR (CONT'D)
It is impossible to say how first the idea entered my brain; but once conceived, it haunted me day and night. Object there was none. Passion there was none. I loved the old man. He had never wronged me. He had never given me insult. For his gold I had no desire. I think it was his eye! yes, it was this!

INT. OLD MAN'S BEDCHAMBER - DAY

THE OLD MAN sits by a shuttered window: elderly, thin, white hair, wrapped in a dark dressing gown. One pale blue eye filmed over—vulture-like—turns toward the doorway.

The Narrator stands in the threshold with a breakfast tray, smiling too brightly. The filmed eye catches the light. The Narrator's smile freezes; his blood runs cold.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
He had the eye of a vulture—a pale blue eye, with a film over it. Whenever it fell upon me, my blood ran cold; and so by degrees—very gradually—I made up my mind to take the life of the old man, and thus rid myself of the eye forever.

INT. HALLWAY OUTSIDE OLD MAN'S BEDCHAMBER - NIGHT

Midnight. The house is black. The Narrator, in shirtsleeves, holds a dark lantern fully closed. He turns the latch—oh, so gently—and opens the door a crack.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
Now this is the point. You fancy me mad. Madmen know nothing. But you should have seen me. You should have seen how wisely I proceeded—with what caution—with what foresight—with what dissimulation I went to work! I was never kinder to the old man than during the whole week before I killed him.

He eases the door wider, thrusts the closed lantern in, then his head—slowly, very, very slowly.

INT. OLD MAN'S BEDCHAMBER - NIGHT

The Old Man sleeps. The Narrator's head is inside the opening. He undoes the lantern just enough: a single thin ray seeks the pillow.

The eye is closed.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
And this I did for seven long nights—every night just at midnight—but I found the eye always closed; and so it was impossible to do the work; for it was not the old man who vexed me, but his Evil Eye.

INT. OLD MAN'S BEDCHAMBER - DAY

Morning light through shutters. The Narrator enters boldly, hearty, throws open the room.

NARRATOR
And how have you passed the night?

The Old Man, filmed eye half-lidded, nods, unsuspecting. The Narrator clasps his shoulder with false warmth.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
So you see he would have been a very profound old man, indeed, to suspect that every night, just at twelve, I looked in upon him while he slept.

INT. HALLWAY OUTSIDE OLD MAN'S BEDCHAMBER - NIGHT

The eighth night. The Narrator at the door, triumphant, almost chuckling. His hand on the latch moves slower than a watch's minute hand.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
Upon the eighth night I was more than usually cautious in opening the door. Never before that night had I felt the extent of my own powers—of my sagacity. I could scarcely contain my feelings of triumph.

A soft chuckle escapes him.

INT. OLD MAN'S BEDCHAMBER - CONTINUOUS

Pitch black—shutters close fastened. The Old Man stirs on the bed, startled.

The Narrator freezes in the opening, still pushing the door steadily, steadily. He has his head in, about to open the lantern—

His thumb slips on the tin fastening.

A metallic click.

The Old Man springs up in bed.

OLD MAN
Who's there?

Silence. The Narrator does not move a muscle.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
I kept quite still and said nothing. For a whole hour I did not move a muscle, and in the meantime I did not hear him lie down. He was still sitting up in the bed listening;—just as I have done, night after night, hearkening to the death watches in the wall.

The Old Man sits rigid in the dark, listening. A slight groan—mortal terror, low and stifled.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
Presently I heard a slight groan, and I knew it was the groan of mortal terror. I knew the sound well. I knew what the old man felt, and pitied him, although I chuckled at heart.

The Old Man whispers to himself, trying to believe.

OLD MAN
(whispered, to himself)
It is nothing but the wind in the chimney—it is only a mouse crossing the floor... It is merely a cricket which has made a single chirp.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
All in vain; because Death, in approaching him had stalked with his black shadow before him, and enveloped the victim.

The Narrator opens a very, very little crevice in the lantern. A single dim ray, like the thread of a spider, shoots out and falls full upon the vulture eye.

It is open—wide, wide open.

The Narrator's face twists with fury as he gazes. Dull blue. Hideous veil. Nothing else of the face—only the damned spot.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
And have I not told you that what you mistake for madness is but over-acuteness of the sense?—now, I say, there came to my ears a low, dull, quick sound, such as a watch makes when enveloped in cotton. I knew that sound well, too. It was the beating of the old man's heart.

SOUND: a low, dull, quick thump—soft at first, then quicker, louder.

The Narrator holds the lantern motionless. Scarcely breathes. The hellish tattoo grows.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
It grew quicker and quicker, and louder and louder every instant. The old man's terror must have been extreme! And now at the dead hour of the night, amid the dreadful silence of that old house, so strange a noise as this excited me to uncontrollable terror. I thought the heart must burst. And now a new anxiety seized me—the sound would be heard by a neighbour! The old man's hour had come!

With a loud yell the Narrator throws open the lantern and leaps into the room.

The Old Man shrieks once—once only.

The Narrator drags him to the floor and pulls the heavy bed over him. The Narrator stands, smiling gaily.

Muffled heartbeat continues beneath the bed—many minutes—then ceases.

The Narrator removes the bed. Examines the corpse. Places his hand upon the heart. Holds it there.

NARRATOR
Yes, he was stone, stone dead.

He looks at the filmed eye, open and still.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
His eye would trouble me no more.

INT. OLD MAN'S BEDCHAMBER - LATER THAT NIGHT

Candlelight. The Narrator works hastily, in silence—dismembering: head, arms, legs. A tub catches all. No stain on the floorboards.

He pries up three planks from the flooring, deposits the remains between the scantlings, replaces the boards so cleverly that no human eye could detect anything wrong.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
If still you think me mad, you will think so no longer when I describe the wise precautions I took for the concealment of the body. There was nothing to wash out—no stain of any kind—no blood-spot whatever. I had been too wary for that. A tub had caught all—ha! ha!

He presses the last board flush. Smooths the seam. Four o'clock. Still dark.

A KNOCKING at the street door below. The Narrator's head lifts. A light heart.

INT. STREET DOOR / ENTRY - NIGHT

The Narrator opens the door with a candle. THREE POLICE OFFICERS enter—coats, badges of the era, perfect suavity:

OFFICER REYNOLDS, older, measured; OFFICER BLAKE, broad, watchful; OFFICER COLE, younger, sharp-eyed.

OFFICER REYNOLDS
A shriek was heard by a neighbour during the night. Suspicion of foul play. We are to search the premises.

The Narrator smiles—what had he now to fear?

NARRATOR
Gentlemen—welcome. The shriek was my own, in a dream. The old man is absent in the country. Search—search well.

INT. HOUSE - VARIOUS - NIGHT

The Narrator leads them through rooms, candle high, manner easy. He shows cupboards, passages, the old man's treasures secure and undisturbed.

INT. OLD MAN'S BEDCHAMBER - NIGHT

He brings them at last here. Chairs. In the wild audacity of triumph he places his own seat upon the very spot beneath which reposes the corpse.

NARRATOR
Rest from your fatigues.

The officers sit. Officer Reynolds glances about; Officer Blake checks the shutters; Officer Cole eyes the floor without suspicion.

OFFICER REYNOLDS
All seems in order.

NARRATOR
(cheerily)
Indeed. A quiet house.

They chat of familiar things. The Narrator answers freely—singularly at ease—then a faint change: he pales. A hand to his temple.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
Ere long, I felt myself getting pale and wished them gone. My head ached, and I fancied a ringing in my ears: but still they sat and still chatted.

SOUND: a ringing that becomes a low, dull, quick sound—as a watch makes when enveloped in cotton.

The Narrator talks more freely. The sound gains definiteness. It is not within his ears.

NARRATOR
(more fluent, heightened voice)
—and the weather has been uncommon raw, has it not? I often sit up late reading—

The officers smile, nod, continue pleasantly. They do not hear it.

The heartbeat sound grows. The Narrator gasps for breath. Rises. Argues about trifles in a high key, violent gesticulations.

NARRATOR (CONT'D)
You must search again if you wish! Every board—every nail—I insist I am at ease—perfectly at ease—

He paces with heavy strides. Foams. Raves. Swings his chair and grates it upon the boards—but the noise arises over all.

Louder—louder—louder.

The officers chat and smile.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
Was it possible they heard not? Almighty God!—no, no! They heard!—they suspected!—they knew!—they were making a mockery of my horror!—this I thought, and this I think. But anything was better than this agony! I could bear those hypocritical smiles no longer! I felt that I must scream or die! and now—again!—hark! louder! louder! louder! louder!

He stops over the spot. The sound pounds. His face breaks.

NARRATOR
(shrieking)
Villains! dissemble no more! I admit the deed!—tear up the planks!—here, here!—It is the beating of his hideous heart!

He stabs a finger at the floorboards beneath his feet.

The officers spring up. Officer Reynolds seizes his arm. Officer Blake and Officer Cole drop to the planks, pry—boards lift—

The Narrator, wild-eyed, still pointing, as the dull quick sound seems to fill the room.

FADE OUT.

THE END
